[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. --{ I’m a FIDE Master, coach, and writer. As a kid, I was one of the top players for my age in the United States. I took a long break from chess to play poker professionally. More recently, I worked as a data scientist. In the past few years, I’ve returned to chess as a coach and writer.    My approach to opening preparation draws on my experiences outside of chess in poker and data science. As a poker player, I learned that it’s more important to do what works against my opponents than to play “perfectly”; as a data scientist, I learned to sift through data to find hidden edges.    This course is all about using what actually works in amateur games – not what grandmasters play, or what the engine says is best. Traditionally, the only chess games that were preserved were master games, but these days the Lichess database gives us access to a huge trove of information about what happens in games between all kinds of chess players. It turns out that at most levels  1.Nf3  outperforms the more traditional  1.e4  and  1.d4 .    Why does  1.Nf3  do so well? Well, you’ve probably heard of AlphaZero, the chess-playing AI created by Google. It learns by playing millions of games against itself with no human input on strategy. AlphaZero thinks  1.Nf3  is just about as good as  1.e4 . Yet in human games at the club level,  1.e4  is played in more than 50% of games, whereas  1.Nf3  is played in only about 5%. The advantage of  1.Nf3  is simple: you get to play a move that is just as good, but that your opponents have ten times less experience facing.    I believe the opening is all about confidence and comfort. You want to get “home field advantage” by getting a position you’re confident playing while taking your opponent out of their comfort zone. For that reason, I recommend going for building a “super-castle” with  Nf3 ,  g3 ,  Bg2 , and  O-O  in most lines. This lets you develop your kingside solidly and soundly and makes it very hard for your opponent to attack your king. You will start the game in your comfort zone.    At the same time, I want to take your opponents out of their comfort zone. For that reason, I’ve focused on lesser-known lines that present Black with unusual problems early in the game. While  1.Nf3  allows for many transpositions to main line openings, I’ve avoided those in favor of fresh territory wherever possible. While the lines are offbeat, they’re not unsound. The lines are all engine-checked. I’ve been using this repertoire in blitz and have scored many wins against international masters and even grandmasters.    As a 100 Repertoire, this course gives you a full White repertoire in 100 variations. If you’re the sort of player who likes memorizing endless variations, this course probably isn’t for you. But if you like to prepare your openings as efficiently as possible to open up study time for other parts of chess, while at the same time creating difficult problems for your opponent, I think you’ll really like it. }
