[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Declined #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3{ Rarely played at the amateur level, but fully in line with opening principles: we develop a knight, exert control on the center, and get ready to castle. In short, a good move that many opponents won't be ready to face. }
1. d5{ Our knight prevents ... e5 , so if Black wants to put a pawn in the center, they have to go with the queen pawn.     Of course, putting a pawn in the center and opening lines to develop is fully in line with classical opening principles, so it's no surprise that this is Black's most popular move. }
2. g3{ Preparing to build a 'supercastle' with  Bg2  and  O-O , securing our king, and harmoniously developing the kingside pieces. }
2. Nf6
3. Bg2
3. e6{ Black goes for a Queen's Gambit Declined style setup, planning to get out the kingside pieces and castle quickly. Not unlike our own setup! But Black's bishop on  e7  has fewer active possibilities than ours on  g2 .     Black's position is certainly very solid, but it's not always easy for them to find an active plan, and we have some nice ways of applying pressure without taking any risks. }
4. O-O{ There's no reason not to complete our standard setup. }
4. Be7{ With our kingside setup complete, it's time to challenge the center with a pawn... but which one? }( { In fact, all three options are reasonable: }5.d4 { would transpose to Queen's pawn openings;  e4  (first prepared with }5.d3 { ) would be the King's Indian Attack (another good option) but our main approach in this course will be }5.c4 { . }{    }{ Why? Well, the  c4 -pawn lever plays very well with our bishop on  g2 , prying open the long diagonal. In many lines, we apply long-term pressure on the queenside after opening the long diagonal. } )( { And as always, I'm keeping an eye on the stats: }5.c4 { scores extremely well in practice! } )
5. c4{ Most of the time Black will castle without thinking, but they could take our pawn. }
5. O-O( { Now we have a choice. }6.d4 { would transpose to the mainline of the Catalan, which is of course a great opening, but we'll go in a different direction.    It's worth pointing out that starting with  1.Nf3  gives you many opportunities to transpose to  1.d4  openings, especially the Catalan.    For this course, I've avoided using  d4  main lines to keep our workload as manageable as possible, but if you play the Catalan or later decide to learn it, these transpositions give you many ways to confuse your opponent by tricking them into a line they weren't intending to play. } )
6. b3{ This move has two purposes: it defends  c4  and prepares to develop the dark-squared bishop on the long diagonal.     This is a key turning point. Black has several options, which take the game in different directions. }
6. d4{ Grabbing more space in the center is ambitious, but Black isn't ideally placed to support it. In particular, they would love to have the pawn on  e5  to support it, but they've already spent a move on  e6 . }
7. e3{ As usual, we waste no time blasting away at the  d4 -pawn! }( { Note that }7.Bb2 { would be a mistake, as after }7...c5 { the bishop would be stuck behind the d-pawn. This is a situation we want to avoid. } )
7. c5
8. exd4
8. cxd4{ Now Black would love to follow up with ... Nc6  and ... e5 . Our next move is designed to prevent that. }
9. Ne5{ Preventing ... Nc6 . }
9. Qc7
10. Re1{ We reinforce the knight on  e5 . }
10. Nc6
11. Qe2{ Continuing the plan of maintaining control of  e5 . }
11. Nxe5
12. Qxe5
12. Qxe5
13. Rxe5( { In this endgame our bishop exerts annoying pressure on  b7 , and Black's  d4 -pawn is a potential weakness.    This is a good place to end the trainable variation, but I'll show an interesting exchange sacrifice that could arise after }13...Nd7 14.Re4 Nc5 15.Rxd4 Bf6 16.Bb2 Nd3 17.Bc3 Bxd4 18.Bxd4 { White has interesting compensation for the exchange in the form of central control and pressure on the long diagonal. It's still not easy for Black to get the bishop out. } )
