6. b3{ This move has two purposes: it defends  c4  and prepares to develop the dark-squared bishop on the long diagonal.     This is a key turning point. Black has several options, which take the game in different directions. }
6. c5{ Grabbing more space in the center, certainly a logical approach. }
7. cxd5{ Chipping away at Black's pawn center. }( 7.Bb2?! d4 { is not what we want. The bishop is locked in behind Black's pawn chain. } )
7. Nxd5
8. Nc3{ Challenging Black's knight in the center. }( { We could also start with }8.Bb2 { , which could transpose, but this gives Black a chance to go wrong by trading knights. } )
8. Nxc3{ Trading may look like an easy way for Black to make a draw, but now a key element of our strategy is revealed: After the trades, White's remaining pieces will be much more active. }
9. dxc3
9. Qxd1
10. Rxd1
10. Nc6
11. Be3{ It may not be immediately obvious, but this is a dreadful position for Black because they can't develop the queenside bishop. Our rook covers  d7 , and ... b6  will lead to a disaster on the long diagonal. }
11. b6
12. Ne1{ Other knight moves would also work. }
12. Bb7
13. Rd7{ Black's position collapses. There's no way to save all of the minor pieces. }
