1. Nf3{ Rarely played at the amateur level, but fully in line with opening principles: we develop a knight, exert control on the center, and get ready to castle. In short, a good move that many opponents won't be ready to face. }
1. d5
2. g3{ Preparing to build a 'supercastle' with  Bg2  and  O-O , securing our king, and developing the kingside pieces harmoniously. }
2. c6{ The Slav is one of Black's most solid setups. It looks especially logical when we're already committed to a fianchetto as Black constructs a pawn chain to blunt our bishop on the long diagonal, but don't worry, that bishop will find good work in the end. In fact, it's Black's light-squared bishop that often gets into trouble when it comes outside the pawn chain. }
3. Bg2
3. Nf6( { Black could start with }3...Bf5 { or }3...Bg4 { , but it will probably transpose, as the knight will probably go to  f6  eventually. } )
4. O-O{ So far Black hasn't done anything to make us deviate from our usual setup.     Now there's a big fork in the road depending on whether they develop the bishop to  f5  or  g4 . These moves look similar, but we respond differently in each case. The key to remembering is that in both cases we attack the bishop in its new position. }
4. Bf5
5. c4{ No surprises so far, this is our usual break in the center. }
5. e6
6. Qb3{ The downside of bringing out the  c8 -bishop early is that it weakens  b7 . We take advantage of that to lure Black's queen to an awkward square. }
6. Qb6
7. d3{ The reason we didn't play  d3  until now was to avoid giving Black the option of trading pawns on  c4 , then trading queens on  d1 . That would be fine too, but we're trying to limit the number of structures Black can go for.     We're generally happy if Black trades queens on  b3 , because after  axb3  our rook gets into the game on the a-file. }
7. Nbd7
8. cxd5{ After Black plays ... Nbd7  is often a good moment to trade on  d5 , as they no longer have the option of developing the knight to  c6  after recapturing with the c-pawn. }
8. exd5
9. Qc2{ Having drawn Black's queen offsides, our queen drops back to support  e4 . }
9. Be7
10. Nc3
10. O-O
11. e4{ It's nice when a plan comes together! }
11. dxe4
12. dxe4
12. Bg6
13. Nh4{ Our  e4 -pawn gives us great control of the center.     Next, we can secure our king with  h3  and  Kh2  to free the f-pawn to advance. Once our kingside pawn majority gets rolling it's going to run right over Black's minor pieces. }
