1. Nf3{ Rarely played at the amateur level, but fully in line with opening principles: we develop a knight, exert control on the center, and get ready to castle. In short, a good move that many opponents won't be ready to face. }
1. d5
2. g3{ Preparing to build a 'supercastle' with  Bg2  and  O-O , securing our king, and harmoniously developing the kingside pieces. }
2. Nc6{ Black goes for a sort of reversed Jobava London. If allowed, they would play ... e5  next move. }
3. d4{ As is often the case, if Black threatens to play ... e5 , we respond with  d4 . Here, it makes even more sense than usual, because the knight on  c6 , blocking the c-pawn, is awkwardly placed in a double queen pawn structure. }
3. Bg4
4. Bg2
4. Qd7
5. O-O
5. Bh3
6. Bxh3{ This seems to give Black just what they want: bringing their queen near our king for an attack. But they lack the firepower to create real threats, and with the queen dragged to the board, we'll counterattack in the center and queenside. }
6. Qxh3
7. c4
7. e6
8. cxd5
8. exd5
9. Nc3
9. O-O-O
10. Bf4{ White's attack on the queenside is coming very quickly, whereas Black has not gotten off the starter's block on the kingside. }
