[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "King's Indian #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3{ Rarely played at the amateur level, but fully in line with opening principles: we develop a knight, exert control on the center, and get ready to castle. In short, a good move that many opponents won't be ready to face. }
1. Nf6
2. g3{ We go for our usual setup. }
2. g6
3. b3{ King's Indian players are usually looking to attack in a double-edged position, so I like to take the wind out of their sails, starting by neutralizing their bishop on the long diagonal. This tricky line gives Black a lot of chances to slip into a passive position and very few attacking opportunities.    It's important to remember to play this now, before  Bg2 , because otherwise Black would beat us to the long diagonal and could create an annoying discovered attack with ... Ne4 . }
3. Bg7
4. Bb2
4. O-O
5. Bg2
5. d5
6. c4{ It's important to do this now, before Black can play ... c5  and answer  c4  with ... d4 . We don't want our bishop on  b2  to be blocked in. }
6. c6
7. O-O{ White's bishops are well-placed on the long diagonals, whereas it's a bit hard for Black to figure out how to develop the queenside pieces effectively. White can finish developing with  d4  and  Nc3 , or  d3  and  Nbd2 , it's quite a flexible position. }
