1. Nf3{ Rarely played at the amateur level, but fully in line with opening principles: we develop a knight, exert control on the center, and get ready to castle. In short, a good move that many opponents won't be ready to face. }
1. c5
2. g3{ As it turns out,  1...c5  is one of the toughest nuts to crack with our usual setup. If you are looking to expand your repertoire, this is a spot I would focus on. You can consider going into an English with  2.c4  or even the Sicilian with  2.e4 .    Those are big branches though, so for this repertoire, we will stick with our standard setup. And there are some interesting possibilities here as well. }
2. Nc6
3. Bg2
3. g6
4. c4{ In some lines it will be useful to delay castling. }
4. Bg7
5. Nc3
5. e6
6. h4{ One reason we delayed castling! We're trying to take advantage of Black's weakened dark squares using the h-pawn.    Black can either ignore the h-pawn’s advance or try to stop it. }
6. h6{ Black's best move, preparing to meet  h5  with ... g5 . Who benefits from the inclusion of  h4  and ... h6 ? There are arguments for both sides:  h6  could be a weakness, but so too could  h4 . Overall it is perhaps a wash, but  h4  is a fun move to play, so why not?! }
7. d4{ A temporary pawn sacrifice to open the position while Black's king is stuck in the center. My goal with playing two unexpected moves in a row -  h4  and  d4  - is to put the opponent on tilt as soon as possible! }
7. cxd4
8. Nb5{ Threatening to jump into  d6 , or regain the pawn on  d4 . }
8. d5{ Black prevents  Nd6 +. }( { Also possible is }8...Nge7 { , when White can choose between }9.Nd6+ { , taking away Black’s right to castle but committing to the pawn sacrifice, or }9.Nbxd4 { , getting the pawn back with a roughly level position. } )
9. cxd5
9. exd5
10. O-O{ There’s no need to recapture the pawn on  d4  just yet as Black can’t defend it, and with the knight on  b5 , they also have to worry about  Bf4  and  Nc7  ideas.    White will get back the sacrificed pawn and can look forward to pressuring Black's isolated d-pawn. }
