7. Ne5{ By attacking the knight on  c6  we immediately put Black to a tough decision. There's only one good way to respond and in the database Black rarely found it. }
7. Bd7{ The only good move, but not an obvious one if you don't know it. Black correctly prioritizes development. }
8. Nxc4{ This simple recapture is rarely played, but I don't know why. It scores well in practice. The idea (apart from just taking a pawn) is to set up an annoying knight check on  d6  before Black can castle. }( 8.Na3 { is more popular, leading to very complex lines requiring a lot of memorization. } )
8. cxd4
9. Bf4{ It is important to do this immediately, setting up  Nd6  before Black has a chance to castle. }
9. Be7
10. Nd6+
10. Kf8{ Consistent with ... Be7 , but giving up the right to castle is a big downside. }( 11...Bxd6?! 12.Bxd6 { If Black wanted to trade the bishop, they shouldn’t have spent a tempo on ... Be7 . } )
11. Nxb7
11. Qb6
12. Nd6( { Now there are many possibilities, but Black's king position is going to be an issue in the resulting positions.    One sample line would be: }12...Qc5 13.b4!? Qxb4 14.a3 Qc5 15.Qb3 Bxd6 16.Rc1! { The queen can't stay in contact with the bishop on  d6 , so White wins. The point of White's play with  b4  was to get a move for  a3 , preventing  ...Qb4  in this position. } )( { Note that }12...e5 { , trying to win our knight, would in fact lose for Black after }13.Nc4! { , hitting the queen and also threatening  Nxe5  because of the pin on the long diagonal. } )
