1. Nf3{ Rarely played at the amateur level, but fully in line with opening principles: we develop a knight, exert control on the center, and get ready to castle. In short, a good move that many opponents won't be ready to face. }
1. d5
2. g3{ Preparing to build a 'supercastle' with  Bg2  and  O-O , securing our king, and developing the kingside pieces harmoniously. }
2. c5{ This is one of Black's most ambitious setups, as well as one of the most common in practice, so pay attention! Black wastes no time trying to take over the center with pawns.     I mentioned that while we have a standard setup on the kingside, we need to be vigilant about what Black is up to. We'll see that in this chapter, as there are some spots where we deviate from our normal setup to avoid giving Black too much of a free hand in the center. }
3. Bg2
3. Nc6{ Our usual plan would be to castle kingside, but here's a spot where we mix it up. Black is ready to take over the center with ... e5 .     Isn't part of our plan to induce Black to build a big pawn center so we can attack it? Yes, but I don't like to give them too much of the center too easily.    I'm happy to give them two pawns in the center, but I don't like to concede three without a fight. That makes this a key move trigger: whenever Black is ready to build the three-pawn wall with  c5 - d5 - e5 , we disrupt them immediately. }
4. d4{ We go for a reversed Grünfeld strategy to disrupt Black's center.     Like the rest of our repertoire, this scores hugely in practice. Why? Well, when White goes into the Grunfeld, they know what they're in for. Because  1.Nf3  is so rare, Black may end up defending a ferocious attack on their center without knowing what they're in for. }
4. Nf6{ Black just develops a knight. Nothing wrong with that! }
5. O-O
5. e6
6. c4{ Throwing another pawn at Black's center. This transposes to the Catalan.     I've avoided transposing to  d4  main lines whenever possible, but in this case, it's just the best option, and I really like White's possibilities in this position. }
6. dxc4
7. Ne5{ By attacking the knight on  c6  we immediately put Black to a tough decision. There's only one good way to respond and in the database Black rarely found it. }
7. Nxe5{ Capturing the invading knight is tempting, and the most popular move in the database, but it leads to a good position for White. }
8. dxe5
8. Qxd1
9. Rxd1
9. Nd5
10. Nc3{ Eliminating Black's only active piece, the knight on  d5 . }
10. Nxc3
11. bxc3
11. Be7
12. a4{ White has more than enough compensation for the pawn. In particular, Black's bishop on  c8  will have a very hard time coming out. We can look forward to ratcheting up the pressure on the queenside. }
