[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3{ Rarely played at the amateur level, but fully in line with opening principles: we develop a knight, exert control on the center, and get ready to castle. In short, a good move that many opponents won't be ready to face. }
1. d5
2. g3{ Preparing to build a 'supercastle' with  Bg2  and  O-O , securing our king, and harmoniously developing the kingside pieces. }
2. g6{ This move is rarely played at the club level, so to be honest, you're somewhat unlikely to face it. But it's considered one of the most solid options at the grandmaster level, so I didn't feel comfortable skipping it altogether.    By playing ... g6  before developing the knight to  f6 , Black has a clever point: the bishop will support a pawn push to  e5 , rapidly taking over the center.    The usual response for White would be to play  d4  to prevent this, but that leads to tedious symmetrical positions with a lot of theory. You can go that way if you want to - Magnus Carlsen has played a lot of games starting that way with great results - but since we're generally trying to avoid  d4  main lines it's not a great fit for this repertoire.    After a bit of digging, I found a line that's much easier to learn and takes the game off the beaten track. }
3. c4{ For reasons we'll see in a moment, it's important to play this immediately. }
3. dxc4
4. Na3{ It's usually preferable to recover the pawn this way, rather than  Qa4 + and  Qxc4 , because it's better to develop the knight before the queen.    The reason we had to play  c4  on move 3 and not later is that in this position if  Bg2  and ... Bg7  were included, Black could play ... e5  and we have no good way of dealing with ... e4 , pushing our knight away. }
4. Bg7
5. Nxc4{ This is a typical structure you could get from the English where we're counting on our 2-to-1 advantage in center pawns to give us a long-term edge. }
5. Nf6
6. Bg2
6. O-O
7. O-O
7. c6
8. b3( { The more standard }8.d4 { would also be fine, but I like contesting Black’s bishop on the long diagonal.    }{ The position may look close to equal, but White scores very well in practice. Black lacks an active plan.    White can finish development with  Bb2 ,  d3 , and  Qc2 . One possible middlegame plan is to go for the minority attack by pushing the queenside pawns:  a4  and  b3 - b4 - b5 . } )
