1. Nf3{ Rarely played at the amateur level, but fully in line with opening principles: we develop a knight, exert control on the center, and get ready to castle. In short, a good move that many opponents won't be ready to face. }
1. c5
2. g3{ As it turns out,  1...c5  is one of the toughest nuts to crack with our usual setup. If you are looking to expand your repertoire, this is a spot I would focus on. You can consider going into an English with  2.c4  or even the Sicilian with  2.e4 .    Those are big branches though, so for this repertoire, we will stick with our standard setup. And there are some interesting possibilities here as well. }
2. Nc6
3. Bg2
3. e5{ Black is trying to use a clever move order to set up the pawn center with  c5 - d5 - e5 . }
4. c4{ As usual, we don't let Black establish the central pawn trifecta  c5 - d5 - e5  without a fight. This will likely end up transposing to lines we cover after  3...g6 . }
4. e4{ Forces our knight to retreat, but overextends in the center. }
5. Ng1
5. Nf6( { After }5...f5 6.d3 Nf6 7.Nc3 { Black can no longer support the center and when the pawns are exchanged, they’ll just be left with weak squares. } )
6. Nc3( { Black doesn't have a good way to maintain the pawn on  e4 . For example, }6...Qe7 7.d3 { and Black has to trade the  e4 -pawn, with nothing but weak squares and discoordinated pieces to show for it. } )
