1. g6{ This is an annoying move order for our repertoire. We can't use the double fianchetto system from the King's Indian chapter, because after  b3   Bg7 , Black would be first to the long diagonal.    Black's move order does have a big downside though: it allows us to play  e4 . This is a pretty big departure from the rest of the repertoire, but it's the most principled move, and I wanted to take the opportunity to show you some of the transpositional possibilities of  1.Nf3 , as well as showing that it might be easier than you think to expand your repertoire. The lines arising from  e4  are a lot of fun and not that hard to learn.    Having said that, if the thought of playing  e4  is already making you break out in hives, you can absolutely use our standard setup with  g3 ,  Bg2 , etc. here. You probably won't get an opening advantage, but this repertoire isn't really about proving an advantage, it's about getting in your comfort zone. }
2. e4{ We're threatening to take over the center with  d4 , so Black's options are fairly limited. If they want to contest the center they have to play ... c5 , transposing to an Accelerated Dragon Sicilian. Or they can play ... Bg7 , allowing us to build a pawn center and go into the Modern Defense. }
2. c5
3. d4{ We are planning to recapture with the queen to exploit the temporarily vulnerable position of the rook on  h8 .    Black can either capture this pawn or ignore it. }
3. cxd4
4. Qxd4{ Taking advantage of the open long diagonal to get our queen in the center with tempo. }( 4.Nxd4 { would transpose to a standard Dragon variation of the Sicilian, which is not what we're after. } )
4. Nf6
5. Nc3{ Apart from being a solid developing move, this increases the strength of  e5  by taking control of the  d5 -square, removing the Black knight's only good jump. }( 5.e5 { is the beginning of a long theoretical line: }5...Nc6 6.Qa4 Nd5 7.Qe4 Ndb4 8.Bb5 Qa5 { and it keeps going from here. This is a bit too much memorization for my taste. I prefer a simpler route. } )
5. Nc6
6. Qa4{ Now we want to drive Black's knight back with  e5 . }
6. d6{ Fighting against  e5 , but walking into a pin. }( 6...Bg7 { is the most common move in the Lichess database, ignoring the threat of  e5 . Brave, but not very smart, because  e5  is a real threat! }7.e5 Ng8 { A sad retreat, but there wasn't a better option. }8.Bf4 { White has a big lead in space and development. Black can barely move any pieces. } )
7. e5{ We use the pin on the knight to keep the initiative going in the center. }
7. dxe5
8. Nxe5
8. Bd7
9. Nxd7
9. Qxd7
10. Be3{ White has a risk-free advantage with the bishop pair and easier development. }
