2. d3{ Okay, please indulge me in one more line where we go  e4 ! Starting with  1.Nf3  gives us the option to play this gambit line against the Dutch, which is a lot of fun and scores insanely well in the Lichess database. }( { Of course, our normal setup with }2.g3 { would also be fine. } )
2. Nf6
3. e4{ This is the point! We're willing to gambit a pawn in the style of a  1.e4  opening to get at Black's king, which they weakened with their first move. }
3. d6{ This is what they usually play at the grandmaster level. Still, White gets a good position quite easily. }
4. exf5
4. Bxf5
5. d4{ It looks odd to play  d4  in two moves, but the position has changed. We prevent Black from playing ... e5  and get ready to trade off the light-squared bishops, accentuating the weak  e6 -square (imagine a knight landing there!). I don't see any advantages for Black to compensate for the weak light squares. }
